<TITLE> Heat wave unlikely to relent soon </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 30 (bdnews24.com)The prevailing heat wave is making life unbearable with load shedding adding to the misery brought about by the sultry weather. Small businesses, schools and public health sectors are also suffering with daytime heat reaching scorching levels. Different educational institutions have curtailed their class hours because of the heat. According to the meteorological department, a moderate heat wave is moving over Dhaka and the southwestern region of the country. The temperature is higher than normal, and there is no possibility of its going down in the next couple of days, weathermen say. Dhaka, Rajshahi and Khulna divisions and a part of Barisal division are also facing mild to moderate heat waves. 39 degrees Celsius was Tuesday's highest recorded temperature in Bogra and Ishwardi. It was 37 degrees Celsius in Dhaka. Sujit Kumar Dev Sharma, chief weatherman of the department said, "The heat may reduce if the monsoon comes within a week." The expected monsoon wind was hovering across the Myanmar coast, he said. Weatherman Sadekul Alam said that the temperature would go down with the monsoon wind. This year the monsoon was being delayed, he added. Doctors have advised people to drink more water and other liquids. Dr Monirul Haque said, " Oral saline would reduce dehydration caused by perspiring. Exposure to the sun should be avoided. Casual, cotton-wear is recommended," he said. bdnews24.c
